style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Rick Hamada, Chief Executive Officer, commented, &#8220;Our team carried the momentum of fiscal 2014 into our new fiscal year as they leveraged continued revenue growth into another year-over-year increase in EPS.  At an enterprise level, year-over-year organic revenue grew </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">5.6%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in constant dollars led by a sixth consecutive quarter of year-over-year organic growth at Electronics Marketing (EM), along with a return to positive growth at Technology Solutions (TS). This top-line growth, combined with an increase in gross profit margin at EM and continued expense efficiencies across the enterprise, resulted in operating income growing 1.6 times faster than revenue and operating income margin increasing </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">13</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points year over year to </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">3.3%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">. Even given an environment of heightened sensitivity to current market conditions, we remain focused on profitable growth opportunities and will continue to align our investments toward maintaining our </font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="s204D20F187196C13DAAADB6779B3E453"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">momentum. style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Mr. Hamada added, &#8220;EM delivered another quarter of top-line growth that was at the high end of expectations and normal seasonality while expanding margins and returns year over year. In the September quarter, revenue increased </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">2.3%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;sequentially in constant currency, primarily due to a </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">10.8%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;increase in Asia partially offset by seasonal declines in the western regions. On a year-over-year basis, EM&#8217;s organic revenue grew </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">7.8%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;led by the Asia region, which increased over </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">13.2%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">. Operating income grew </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">15.3%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;year over year with all three regions delivering double digit growth and operating income margin increased </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">17</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;basis points to </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">4.6%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">.  Although September is typically a seasonally weak quarter for EM, our team delivered another quarter of improved financial performance across all regions.  In Asia, where select high volume supply chain engagements are driving much of the current top-line growth, the team continues to increase returns and grow economic profit dollars.  In EMEA, our team delivered a sixth consecutive quarter of year-over-year organic growth, and with the integration of MSC now essentially complete, our team is back to posting year-over-year increases in both margins and returns.  In our Americas region, the team returned to modest year-over-year revenue growth, which drove an increase in both margins and returns.  While our book to bill ratio was slightly above parity at the end of the quarter, we are diligently monitoring our dashboards and we remain committed to driving further improvement in our financial performance as we continue to focus on our goals for the full fiscal year.&#8221;  </font></div><a name="sA4AFEC439055E8A09812DB677A0983A9"></a><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;"><font style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;padding-left:24px;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#9642;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">At a product level, year-over-year growth in software, services, and networking and security, was partially offset by a decline in computing components</font></div></td></tr></table><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;padding-left:24px;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Mr. Hamada further added, "During our September quarter, TS delivered top-line growth of </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">2.4%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;year over year driven by strength in our Americas region, which experienced double digit organic growth for the first time in three years.  In our EMEA region, which declined </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">5.8%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in constant currency, mid-single digit growth in our core enterprise distribution business was offset by a decline in our computing components business.  TS Asia was below our expectations this quarter as revenue declined </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">14.6%</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;sequentially with this weakness reflected broadly across the region. In our TS EMEA region, our team has been driving efficiencies as operating income margin improved both sequentially and year over year. Going forward, we will continue to utilize our disciplined portfolio management to ensure we are focusing our resources on high growth opportunities in the enterprise IT ecosystem.&#8221;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><a name="s219F123FD1881A3179FADB677A3BFD39"></a><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:18px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Cash Flow/Dividend</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;text-align:justify;padding-left:20px;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:24px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;padding-left:0px;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#9642;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Cash used for operations was </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$40.7 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in the September quarter and for the trailing twelve months, cash generated from operations was </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$323.0 million</font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; net debt (total debt less cash and cash equivalents) was approximately </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;">$1.3 billion</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;</font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; Entering the second quarter, the Company had approximately </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;color:#000000;">$198 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;remaining under the current authorization</font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:24px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:11pt;padding-left:0px;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#9642;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">The Company paid a quarterly dividend of </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;color:#000000;text-decoration:none;">$0.16</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;per share or </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$22.1 million</font></div></td></tr></table><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Kevin Moriarty, Chief Financial Officer, stated, &#8220;We used roughly </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$41 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;in cash flow to fund operations for the quarter as the working capital grew to support our organic sales growth. Despite the use of cash during the quarter, the trailing twelve months cash flow generated from operations improved by 36% to </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$323 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">, and we exited the quarter with roughly </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$814 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;of cash on our balance sheet.  Our disciplined </font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">approach to our capital allocation priorities has positioned us well for the recent equity market environment and, during the quarter, we returned approximately $40 million to shareholders.  In the September quarter, we raised our quarterly dividend by 7% to an annualized $0.64 a year, or </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$22 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;per quarter, while also repurchasing approximately </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$18 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;of shares through our share repurchase program. We began our fiscal second quarter with approximately </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">$198 million</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">&#32;remaining under our currently authorized share repurchase program, and through the first three weeks of our second fiscal quarter have repurchased approximately $55 million of shares. As of the end of September, we have over $2.0 billion of liquidity to support continued organic growth initiatives, invest in value creating M&amp;A and shareholder returns.&#8221;   </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><a name="s644EE75A7101D3BBC109DB677A59C014"></a><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:18px;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Outlook for </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Second</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">&#32;Quarter of Fiscal </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">2015</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">&#32;Ending on </font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">December&#160;27, 2014</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">&#32;</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;text-align:left;padding-left:20px;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; In addition, the above guidance assumes that the average U.S. Dollar to Euro currency exchange rate for the second quarter of fiscal 2015 is $1.27 to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#8364;</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">1.00. This compares with an average exchange rate of $1.36 to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#8364;</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">1.00 in the second quarter of fiscal 2014 and $1.33 to </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:11pt;">&#8364;</font><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">1.00 in the first quarter of fiscal 2015. </font></div><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><a name="sB937CFD9DA487AB19D42DB674C7FCC7C"></a><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:18px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Forward-Looking Statements</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">This document contains certain &#8220;forward-looking statements&#8221; within the meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. These statements are based on management&#8217;s current expectations and are subject to uncertainty and changes in facts and circumstances. The forward-looking statements herein include statements addressing future financial and operating results of Avnet and may include words such as &#8220;will,&#8221; &#8220;anticipate,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;forecast,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; "feel," &#8220;believe,&#8221; and &#8220;should,&#8221; and other words and terms of similar meaning in connection with any discussions of future operating or financial performance, business prospects or market conditions. Actual results may differ materially from the expectations contained in the forward-looking statements.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">The following factors, among others, could cause actual results to differ materially from those described in the forward-looking statements: the Company&#8217;s ability to retain and grow market share and to generate additional cash flow, risks associated with any acquisition activities and the successful integration of acquired companies, declines in sales, changes in business conditions and the economy in general, changes in market demand and pricing pressures, any material changes in the allocation of product or product rebates by suppliers, and other competitive and/or regulatory factors affecting the businesses of Avnet generally.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">More detailed information about these and other factors is set forth in Avnet&#8217;s filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, including the Company&#8217;s reports on Form 10-K, Form 10-Q and Form 8-K. Except as required by law, Avnet is under no obligation to update any forward-looking statements, whether as a result of new information, future events or otherwise.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:18px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Non-GAAP Financial Information</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">In addition to disclosing financial results that are determined in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;), the Company also discloses in this document certain non-GAAP financial information including adjusted operating income, adjusted net income and adjusted diluted earnings per share, as well as sales adjusted for the impact of acquisitions and other items (as </font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">defined in the Organic Sales section of this document). Management believes organic sales is a useful measure for evaluating current period performance as compared with prior periods and for understanding underlying trends.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Management believes that operating income adjusted for (i) restructuring, integration and other expenses and (ii) amortization of acquired intangible assets and other, is a useful measure to help investors better assess and understand the Company&#8217;s operating performance, especially when comparing results with previous periods or forecasting performance for future periods, primarily because management views the excluded items to be outside of Avnet&#8217;s normal operating results or non-cash in nature. Management analyzes operating income without the impact of these items as an indicator of ongoing margin performance and underlying trends in the business. Management also uses these non-GAAP measures to establish operational goals and, in some cases, for measuring performance for compensation purposes.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Management believes net income and diluted EPS adjusted for (i) the impact of the items described above, (ii) certain items impacting income tax expense and (iii) the gain on legal settlement, is useful to investors because it provides a measure of the Company&#8217;s net profitability on a more comparable basis to historical periods and provides a more meaningful basis for forecasting future performance. Additionally, because of management&#8217;s focus on generating shareholder value, of which net profitability is a primary driver, management believes net income and diluted EPS excluding the impact of these items provides an important measure of the Company&#8217;s net results for the investing public.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;">Other metrics management monitors in its assessment of business performance include return on working capital (ROWC), return on capital employed (ROCE) and working capital velocity (WC velocity).</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:74px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;text-align:justify;padding-left:74px;font-size:11pt;"><font style="font-family:Arial;font-size:11pt;"><br></font></div><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" The year-over-year decline is primarily due to improved operating leverage from increased gross profits and the impact of restructuring actions taken. </font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:72px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:48px;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#9702;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">TS SG&amp;A expenses as a percent of gross profit increased 207 basis points sequentially and </font><font style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;font-style:normal;font-weight:normal;text-decoration:none;">12</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#32;basis points from the year ago quarter. Q1 Fiscal Year 2015</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">$ in millions - except per share data</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">October 23, 2014</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Forward-Looking Statements</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">This document contains certain &#8220;forward-looking statements&#8221; within the meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and Section 21E of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended. These statements are based on management&#8217;s current expectations and are subject to uncertainty and changes in facts and circumstances. The forward-looking statements herein include statements addressing future financial and operating results of Avnet and may include words such as &#8220;will,&#8221; &#8220;anticipate,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;forecast,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;believe,&#8221; and &#8220;should,&#8221; and other words and terms of similar meaning in connection with any discussions of future operating or financial performance, business prospects or market conditions. Actual results may differ materially from the expectations contained in the forward-looking statements.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">The following factors, among others, could cause actual results to differ materially from those described in the forward-looking statements: the Company&#8217;s ability to retain and grow market share and to generate additional cash flow, risks associated with any acquisition activities and the successful integration of acquired companies, declines in sales, changes in business conditions and the economy in general, changes in market demand and pricing pressures, any material changes in the allocation of product or product rebates by suppliers, and other competitive and/or regulatory factors affecting the businesses of Avnet generally.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">More detailed information about these and other factors is set forth in Avnet&#8217;s filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, including the Company&#8217;s reports on Form 10-K, Form 10-Q and Form 8-K. Except as required by law, Avnet is under no obligation to update any forward-looking statements, whether as a result of new information, future events or otherwise.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Organic Sales</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-left:4px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Organic sales is defined as reported sales adjusted for  the impact of acquisitions and divestitures by adjusting Avnet&#8217;s prior periods to include the sales of acquired businesses and exclude the sales of divested businesses as if the acquisitions and divestitures had occurred at the beginning of the earliest period presented.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;">Non-GAAP Financial Information</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">In addition to disclosing financial results that are determined in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;), the Company also discloses in this document certain non-GAAP financial information including adjusted operating income, adjusted net income and adjusted diluted earnings per share, as well as sales adjusted for the impact of acquisitions and other items (as defined in the Organic Sales section of this document). Management believes organic sales is a useful measure for evaluating current period performance as compared with prior periods and for understanding underlying trends.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Management believes that operating income adjusted for (i) restructuring, integration and other expenses, and (ii) amortization of acquired intangible assets and other, is a useful measure to help investors better assess and understand the Company&#8217;s operating performance, especially when comparing results with previous periods or forecasting performance for future periods, primarily because management views the excluded items to be outside of Avnet&#8217;s normal operating results or non-cash in nature. Management analyzes operating income without the impact of these items as an indicator of ongoing margin performance and underlying trends in the business. Management also uses these non-GAAP measures to establish operational goals and, in some cases, for measuring performance for compensation purposes.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Management believes net income and diluted EPS adjusted for (i) the impact of the items described above, (ii) certain items impacting income tax expense and (iii) the gain on legal settlement is useful to investors because it provides a measure of the Company&#8217;s net profitability on a more comparable basis to historical periods and provides a more meaningful basis for forecasting future performance. Additionally, because of management&#8217;s focus on generating shareholder value, of which net profitability is a primary driver, management believes net income and diluted EPS excluding the impact of these items provides an important measure of the Company&#8217;s net results for the investing public.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Other metrics management monitors in its assessment of business performance include return on working capital (ROWC), return on capital employed (ROCE) and working capital velocity (WC velocity).</font></div><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="padding-top:6px;font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:66px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:48px;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#8226;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">ROWC is defined as annualized adjusted operating income (as defined above) divided by the sum of the monthly average balances of receivables and inventories less accounts payable.</font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="padding-top:6px;font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:66px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:48px;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#8226;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">ROCE is defined as annualized, tax effected adjusted operating income (as defined above) divided by the monthly average balances of interest-bearing debt and equity (including the impact of adjustments to operating income discussed above) less cash and cash equivalents.</font></div></td></tr></table><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="padding-top:6px;font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt;"><tr><td style="width:66px;"></td><td></td></tr><tr><td style="vertical-align:top"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;padding-left:48px;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#8226;</font></div></td><td style="vertical-align:top;"><div style="line-height:120%;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">WC velocity is defined as annualized sales divided by the sum of the monthly average balances of receivables and inventories less accounts payable.</font></div></td></tr></table><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><a name="s1CDF38252F15AF8F532EDB677F1D4EC7"></a><div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Avnet, Inc. Q1 Fiscal Year 2015</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">$ in millions - except per share data</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">October 23, 2014</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div><br><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:12px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">Any analysis of results and outlook on a non-GAAP basis should be used as a complement to, and in conjunction with, results presented in accordance with GAAP. A reconciliation of the GAAP financial measures to the non-GAAP financial measures is included in the Company&#8217;s press release dated </font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">October&#160;23, 2014</font><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;">&#32;(Exhibit 99.1) in this Current Report on Form 8-K.</font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><div style="line-height:120%;padding-top:6px;text-align:justify;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div><br><div style="text-align:center;"><div style="line-height:120%;font-size:10pt;"><font style="font-family:inherit;font-size:10pt;"><br></font></div></div>	</body>
